[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In logic and computer science, the **Boolean satisfiability problem** (sometimes called **propositional satisfiability problem** and abbreviated **SATISFIABILITY**, **SAT** or **B-SAT**) asks whether there exists an interpretation that satisfies a given Boolean formula.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In other words, it asks whether the formula's variables can be consistently replaced by the values TRUE or FALSE to make the formula evaluate to TRUE.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If this is the case, the formula is called *satisfiable*, else *unsatisfiable*.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, the formula "*a* AND NOT *b*" is satisfiable because one can find the values *a* = TRUE and *b* = FALSE, which make (*a* AND NOT *b*) = TRUE.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In contrast, "*a* AND NOT *a*" is unsatisfiable.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is the first problem that was proven to be NP-complete—this is the Cook–Levin theorem.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This means that all problems in the complexity class NP, which includes a wide range of natural decision and optimization problems, are at most as difficult to solve as SAT.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] There is no known algorithm that efficiently solves each SAT problem (where "efficiently" means "deterministically in polynomial time").
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Although such an algorithm is generally believed not to exist, this belief has not been proven or disproven mathematically.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Resolving the question of whether SAT has a polynomial-time algorithm would settle the P versus NP problem - one of the most important open problems in the theory of computing.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Nevertheless, heuristic SAT-algorithms are able to solve problem instances involving tens of thousands of variables and formulas consisting of millions of symbols, which is sufficient for many practical SAT problems occurring in artificial intelligence, circuit design, and automatic theorem proving.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *propositional logic formula*, also called *Boolean expression*, is built from variables, operators AND (conjunction, also denoted by ∧), OR (disjunction, ∨), NOT (negation, ¬), and parentheses.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A formula is said to be *satisfiable* if it can be made TRUE by assigning appropriate logical values (i.e.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The *Boolean satisfiability problem* (SAT) is, given a formula, to check whether it is satisfiable.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This decision problem is of central importance in many areas of computer science, including theoretical computer science, complexity theory, algorithmics, cryptography and artificial intelligence.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *literal* is either a variable (in which case it is called a *positive literal*) or the negation of a variable (called a *negative literal*).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *clause* is a disjunction of literals (or a single literal).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A clause is called a *Horn clause* if it contains at most one positive literal.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A formula is in *conjunctive normal form* (CNF) if it is a conjunction of clauses (or a single clause).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, *x*1 is a positive literal, ¬*x*2 is a negative literal, and *x*1 ∨ ¬*x*2 is a clause.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula (*x*1 ∨ ¬*x*2) ∧ (¬*x*1 ∨ *x*2 ∨ *x*3) ∧ ¬*x*1 is in conjunctive normal form; its first and third clauses are Horn clauses, but its second clause is not.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula is satisfiable, by choosing *x*1 = FALSE, *x*2 = FALSE, and *x*3 arbitrarily, since (FALSE ∨ ¬FALSE) ∧ (¬FALSE ∨ FALSE ∨ *x*3) ∧ ¬FALSE evaluates to (FALSE ∨ TRUE) ∧ (TRUE ∨ FALSE ∨ *x*3) ∧ TRUE, and in turn to TRUE ∧ TRUE ∧ TRUE (i.e. to TRUE).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In contrast, the CNF formula *a* ∧ ¬*a*, consisting of two clauses of one literal, is unsatisfiable, since for *a*=TRUE or *a*=FALSE it evaluates to TRUE ∧ ¬TRUE (i.e., FALSE) or FALSE ∧ ¬FALSE (i.e., again FALSE), respectively.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For some versions of the SAT problem, it is useful to define the notion of a *generalized conjunctive normal form* formula, viz. as a conjunction of arbitrarily many *generalized clauses*, the latter being of the form *R*(*l*1,...,*l**n*) for some Boolean function *R* and (ordinary) literals *l**i*.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Different sets of allowed Boolean functions lead to different problem versions.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This formula is used below, with *R* being the ternary operator that is TRUE just when exactly one of its arguments is.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Using the laws of Boolean algebra, every propositional logic formula can be transformed into an equivalent conjunctive normal form, which may, however, be exponentially longer.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] while the former is a disjunction of *n* conjunctions of 2 variables, the latter consists of 2*n* clauses of *n* variables.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] However, with use of the Tseytin transformation, we may find an equisatisfiable conjunctive normal form formula with length linear in the size of the original propositional logic formula.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT was the first problem known to be NP-complete, as proved by Stephen Cook at the University of Toronto in 1971 and independently by Leonid Levin at the Russian Academy of Sciences in 1973.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Until that time, the concept of an NP-complete problem did not even exist.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The proof shows how every decision problem in the complexity class NP can be reduced to the SAT problem for CNF formulas, sometimes called **CNFSAT**.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A useful property of Cook's reduction is that it preserves the number of accepting answers.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, deciding whether a given graph has a 3-coloring is another problem in NP; if a graph has 17 valid 3-colorings, then the SAT formula produced by the Cook–Levin reduction will have 17 satisfying assignments.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] NP-completeness only refers to the run-time of the worst case instances.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Many of the instances that occur in practical applications can be solved much more quickly.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Like the satisfiability problem for arbitrary formulas, determining the satisfiability of a formula in conjunctive normal form where each clause is limited to at most three literals is NP-complete also; this problem is called **3-SAT**, **3CNFSAT**, or **3-satisfiability**.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] where *x*2, ⋯ , *x**n*−2 are fresh variables not occurring elsewhere.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Although the two formulas are not logically equivalent, they are equisatisfiable.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula resulting from transforming all clauses is at most 3 times as long as its original; that is, the length growth is polynomial.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] 3-SAT is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems, and it is used as a starting point for proving that other problems are also NP-hard.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This is done by polynomial-time reduction from 3-SAT to the other problem.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An example of a problem where this method has been used is the clique problem: given a CNF formula consisting of *c* clauses, the corresponding graph consists of a vertex for each literal, and an edge between each two non-contradicting literals from different clauses; see the picture.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The graph has a *c*-clique if and only if the formula is satisfiable.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] There is a simple randomized algorithm due to Schöning (1999) that runs in time (4/3)*n* where *n* is the number of variables in the 3-SAT proposition, and succeeds with high probability to correctly decide 3-SAT.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The exponential time hypothesis asserts that no algorithm can solve 3-SAT (or indeed *k*-SAT for any *k* > 2) in exp(*o*(*n*)) time (that is, fundamentally faster than exponential in *n*).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Selman, Mitchell, and Levesque (1996) give empirical data on the difficulty of randomly generated 3-SAT formulas, depending on their size parameters.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Difficulty is measured in number recursive calls made by a DPLL algorithm.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] They identified a phase transition region from almost-certainly-satisfiable to almost-certainly-unsatisfiable formulas at the clauses-to-variables ratio at about 4.26.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] 3-satisfiability can be generalized to **k-satisfiability** (**k-SAT**, also **k-CNF-SAT**), when formulas in CNF are considered with each clause containing up to k literals.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] However, since for any *k* ≥ 3, this problem can neither be easier than 3-SAT nor harder than SAT, and the latter two are NP-complete, so must be k-SAT.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Some authors restrict k-SAT to CNF formulas with **exactly k literals**.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This does not lead to a different complexity class either, as each clause with fewer than k literals can be padded with repeated copies of the same literals.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Satisfiability and solution space geometry of k-SAT problems with randomly generated clauses have been investigated statistically.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] As a function of the clause-to-variable ratio (also known as the density), the model exhibits various phase transitions regarding satisfiability and solution space geometry.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For satisfiability, there exists a sharp threshold such that with high probability a solution exists if and only if the density remains below this threshold.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Well below the satisfiability threshold, the solution space also undergoes a geometric phase transition, namely that it shatters into exponentially many, well-separated clusters.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The onset of this phase transition coincides with the known algorithmic threshold, suggesting a link between geometry and algorithmic intractability.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Conjunctive normal form (in particular with 3 literals per clause) is often considered the canonical representation for SAT formulas.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] As shown above, the general SAT problem reduces to 3-SAT, the problem of determining satisfiability for formulas in this form.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A 3-SAT formula is *Linear SAT* (*LSAT*) if each clause (viewed as a set of literals) intersects at most one other clause, and, moreover, if two clauses intersect, then they have exactly one literal in common.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An LSAT formula can be depicted as a set of disjoint semi-closed intervals on a line.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Deciding whether an LSAT formula is satisfiable is NP-complete.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is easier if the number of literals in a clause is limited to at most 2, in which case the problem is called **2-SAT**.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This problem can be solved in polynomial time, and in fact is complete for the complexity class NL.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If additionally all OR operations in literals are changed to XOR operations, then the result is called **exclusive-or 2-satisfiability**, which is a problem complete for the complexity class SL = L.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The problem of deciding the satisfiability of a given conjunction of Horn clauses is called **Horn-satisfiability**, or **HORN-SAT**.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It can be solved in polynomial time by a single step of the unit propagation algorithm, which produces the single minimal model of the set of Horn clauses (w.r.t. the set of literals assigned to TRUE).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It can be seen as P's version of the Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Also, deciding the truth of quantified Horn formulas can be done in polynomial time.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Horn clauses are of interest because they are able to express implication of one variable from a set of other variables.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A generalization of the class of Horn formulas is that of renameable-Horn formulae, which is the set of formulas that can be placed in Horn form by replacing some variables with their respective negation.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Checking the existence of such a replacement can be done in linear time; therefore, the satisfiability of such formulae is in P as it can be solved by first performing this replacement and then checking the satisfiability of the resulting Horn formula.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is trivial if the formulas are restricted to those in **disjunctive normal form**, that is, they are a disjunction of conjunctions of literals.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Such a formula is indeed satisfiable if and only if at least one of its conjunctions is satisfiable, and a conjunction is satisfiable if and only if it does not contain both *x* and NOT *x* for some variable *x*.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Furthermore, if they are restricted to being in **full disjunctive normal form**, in which every variable appears exactly once in every conjunction, they can be checked in constant time (each conjunction represents one satisfying assignment).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] But it can take exponential time and space to convert a general SAT problem to disjunctive normal form; to obtain an example, exchange "∧" and "∨" in the above exponential blow-up example for conjunctive normal forms.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another NP-complete variant of the 3-satisfiability problem is the **one-in-three 3-SAT** (also known variously as **1-in-3-SAT** and **exactly-1 3-SAT**).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Given a conjunctive normal form with three literals per clause, the problem is to determine whether there exists a truth assignment to the variables so that each clause has *exactly* one TRUE literal (and thus exactly two FALSE literals).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another variant is the **not-all-equal 3-satisfiability** problem (also called **NAE3SAT**).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Given a conjunctive normal form with three literals per clause, the problem is to determine if an assignment to the variables exists such that in no clause all three literals have the same truth value.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This problem is NP-complete, too, even if no negation symbols are admitted, by Schaefer's dichotomy theorem.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another special case is the class of problems where each clause contains XOR (i.e. exclusive or) rather than (plain) OR operators.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This is in P, since an XOR-SAT formula can also be viewed as a system of linear equations mod 2, and can be solved in cubic time by Gaussian elimination.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The restrictions above (CNF, 2CNF, 3CNF, Horn, XOR-SAT) bound the considered formulae to be conjunctions of subformulas; each restriction states a specific form for all subformulas: for example, only binary clauses can be subformulas in 2CNF.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Schaefer's dichotomy theorem states that, for any restriction to Boolean functions that can be used to form these subformulas, the corresponding satisfiability problem is in P or NP-complete.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The membership in P of the satisfiability of 2CNF, Horn, and XOR-SAT formulae are special cases of this theorem.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The following table summarizes some common variants of SAT.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An extension that has gained significant popularity since 2003 is **satisfiability modulo theories** (**SMT**) that can enrich CNF formulas with linear constraints, arrays, all-different constraints, uninterpreted functions, etc.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Such extensions typically remain NP-complete, but very efficient solvers are now available that can handle many such kinds of constraints.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The satisfiability problem becomes more difficult if both "for all" (∀) and "there exists" (∃) quantifiers are allowed to bind the Boolean variables.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An example of such an expression would be ∀*x* ∀*y* ∃*z* (*x* ∨ *y* ∨ *z*) ∧ (¬*x* ∨ ¬*y* ∨ ¬*z*); it is valid, since for all values of *x* and *y*, an appropriate value of *z* can be found, viz.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] *z*=TRUE if both *x* and *y* are FALSE, and *z*=FALSE else.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT itself (tacitly) uses only ∃ quantifiers.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If only ∀ quantifiers are allowed instead, the so-called **tautology problem** is obtained, which is co-NP-complete.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If any number of both quantifiers are allowed, the problem is called the **quantified Boolean formula problem** (**QBF**), which can be shown to be PSPACE-complete.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It is widely believed that PSPACE-complete problems are strictly harder than any problem in NP, although this has not yet been proved.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Ordinary SAT asks if there is at least one variable assignment that makes the formula true.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Other generalizations include satisfiability for first- and second-order logic, constraint satisfaction problems, 0-1 integer programming.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] While SAT is a decision problem, the search problem of finding a satisfying assignment reduces to SAT.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] That is, each algorithm which correctly answers whether an instance of SAT is solvable can be used to find a satisfying assignment.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] First, the question is asked on the given formula Φ.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If the answer is "no", the formula is unsatisfiable.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Otherwise, the question is asked on the partly instantiated formula Φ{*x*1=TRUE}, that is, Φ with the first variable *x*1 replaced by TRUE, and simplified accordingly.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If the answer is "yes", then *x*1=TRUE, otherwise *x*1=FALSE.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Values of other variables can be found subsequently in the same way.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In total, *n*+1 runs of the algorithm are required, where *n* is the number of distinct variables in Φ.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Since the SAT problem is NP-complete, only algorithms with exponential worst-case complexity are known for it.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In spite of this, efficient and scalable algorithms for SAT were developed during the 2000s and have contributed to dramatic advances in the ability to automatically solve problem instances involving tens of thousands of variables and millions of constraints (i.e. clauses).
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Examples of such problems in electronic design automation (EDA) include formal equivalence checking, model checking, formal verification of pipelined microprocessors, automatic test pattern generation, routing of FPGAs, planning, and scheduling problems, and so on.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A SAT-solving engine is also considered to be an essential component in the electronic design automation toolbox.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Major techniques used by modern SAT solvers include the Davis–Putnam–Logemann–Loveland algorithm (or DPLL), conflict-driven clause learning (CDCL), and stochastic local search algorithms such as WalkSAT.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Almost all SAT solvers include time-outs, so they will terminate in reasonable time even if they cannot find a solution.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Different SAT solvers will find different instances easy or hard, and some excel at proving unsatisfiability, and others at finding solutions.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Recent attempts have been made to learn an instance's satisfiability using deep learning techniques.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT solvers are developed and compared in SAT-solving contests.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Modern SAT solvers are also having significant impact on the fields of software verification, constraint solving in artificial intelligence, and operations research, among others.
[src:proof-complexity/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Earlier runtime guarantees are shown in the diagram.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] In mathematical optimization, the **cutting-plane method** is any of a variety of optimization methods that iteratively refine a feasible set or objective function by means of linear inequalities, termed *cuts*.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Such procedures are commonly used to find integer solutions to mixed integer linear programming (MILP) problems, as well as to solve general, not necessarily differentiable convex optimization problems.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The use of cutting planes to solve MILP was introduced by Ralph E.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods for MILP work by solving a non-integer linear program, the linear relaxation of the given integer program.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The theory of Linear Programming dictates that under mild assumptions (if the linear program has an optimal solution, and if the feasible region does not contain a line), one can always find an extreme point or a corner point that is optimal.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The obtained optimum is tested for being an integer solution.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] If it is not, there is guaranteed to exist a linear inequality that *separates* the optimum from the convex hull of the true feasible set.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Finding such an inequality is the *separation problem*, and such an inequality is a *cut*.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] A cut can be added to the relaxed linear program.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Then, the current non-integer solution is no longer feasible to the relaxation.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] This process is repeated until an optimal integer solution is found.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Cutting-plane methods for general convex continuous optimization and variants are known under various names: Kelley's method, Kelley–Cheney–Goldstein method, and bundle methods.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] They are popularly used for non-differentiable convex minimization, where a convex objective function and its subgradient can be evaluated efficiently but usual gradient methods for differentiable optimization can not be used.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] This situation is most typical for the concave maximization of Lagrangian dual functions.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Another common situation is the application of the Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition to a structured optimization problem in which formulations with an exponential number of variables are obtained.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Generating these variables on demand by means of delayed column generation is identical to performing a cutting plane on the respective dual problem.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Cutting planes were proposed by Ralph Gomory in the 1950s as a method for solving integer programming and mixed-integer programming problems.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] However, most experts, including Gomory himself, considered them to be impractical due to numerical instability, as well as ineffective because many rounds of cuts were needed to make progress towards the solution.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Things turned around when in the mid-1990s Gérard Cornuéjols and co-workers showed them to be very effective in combination with branch-and-bound (called branch-and-cut) and ways to overcome numerical instabilities.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Nowadays, all commercial MILP solvers use Gomory cuts in one way or another.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Gomory cuts are very efficiently generated from a simplex tableau, whereas many other types of cuts are either expensive or even NP-hard to separate.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Among other general cuts for MILP, most notably lift-and-project dominates Gomory cuts.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] where A is a matrix and b , c is a vector.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The vector x is unknown and is to be found in order to maximize the objective while respecting the linear constraints.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The method proceeds by first dropping the requirement that the xi be integers and solving the associated relaxed linear programming problem to obtain a basic feasible solution.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Geometrically, this solution will be a vertex of the convex polytope consisting of all feasible points.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] If this vertex is not an integer point then the method finds a hyperplane with the vertex on one side and all feasible integer points on the other.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] This is then added as an additional linear constraint to exclude the vertex found, creating a modified linear program.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The new program is then solved and the process is repeated until an integer solution is found.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] where *xi* is a basic variable and the *xj'*s are the nonbasic variables (i.e. the basic solution which is an optimal solution to the relaxed linear program is $x_{i}={\bar {b}}_{i}$ and $x_{j}=0$ ).
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] We write coefficients ${\bar {b}}_{i}$ and ${\bar {a}}_{i,j}$ with a bar to denote the last tableau produced by the simplex method.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] These coefficients are different from the coefficients in the matrix A and the vector b.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Consider now a basic variable $x_{i}$ which is not an integer.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] For any integer point in the feasible region, the left side is an integer since all the terms $x_{i}$ , $x_{j}$ , $\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor$ , $\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ are integers.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The right side of this equation is strictly less than 1: indeed, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ is strictly less than 1 while $-\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Therefore the common value must be less than or equal to 0.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] must hold for any integer point in the feasible region.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] So the inequality above excludes the basic feasible solution and thus is a cut with the desired properties.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] More precisely, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor -\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative for any integer point in the feasible region, and strictly positive for the basic feasible (non integer) solution of the relaxed linear program.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods are also applicable in nonlinear programming.
[src:proof-complexity/cutting-plane-method] The underlying principle is to approximate the feasible region of a nonlinear (convex) program by a finite set of closed half spaces and to solve a sequence of approximating linear programs.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] In proof complexity, a **Frege system** is a propositional proof system whose proofs are sequences of formulas derived using a finite set of sound and implicationally complete inference rules.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] Frege systems (more often known as Hilbert systems in general proof theory) are named after Gottlob Frege.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] The name "Frege system" was first defined by Stephen Cook and Robert Reckhow, and was intended to capture the properties of the most common propositional proof systems.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] Cook and Reckhow gave the first formal definition of a Frege system, to which the one below, based on Krajicek, is equivalent.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] Let *K* be a finite functionally complete set of Boolean connectives, and consider propositional formulas built from variables *p*0, *p*1, *p*2, ... using *K*-connectives.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] If *R* is a finite set of Frege rules, then *F* = (*K*,*R*) defines a derivation system in the following way.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] An *F*-proof of a formula *A* is an *F*-derivation of *A* from the empty set of axioms (X=∅).
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] The length (number of lines) in a proof *A*1, ..., *Am* is *m*.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] The size of the proof is the total number of symbols.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] A derivation system *F* as above is refutationally complete, if for every inconsistent set of formulas *X*, there is an *F*-derivation of a fixed contradiction from *X*.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] The purpose of the new derivation rule is to introduce 'names' or shortcuts for arbitrary formulas.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] It allows one to interpret proofs in Extended Frege as Frege proofs operating with circuits instead of formulas.
[src:proof-complexity/frege-system] Cook's correspondence allows one to interpret Extended Frege as a nonuniform equivalent of Cook's theory PV and Buss's theory $S_{2}^{1}$ formalizing feasible (polynomial-time) reasoning.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In logic and theoretical computer science, and specifically proof theory and computational complexity theory, **proof complexity** is the field aiming to understand and analyse the computational resources that are required to prove or refute statements.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Research in proof complexity is predominantly concerned with proving proof-length lower and upper bounds in various propositional proof systems.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] For example, among the major challenges of proof complexity is showing that the Frege system, the usual propositional calculus, does not admit polynomial-size proofs of all tautologies.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Here the size of the proof is simply the number of symbols in it, and a proof is said to be of polynomial size if it is polynomial in the size of the tautology it proves.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Systematic study of proof complexity began with the work of Stephen Cook and Robert Reckhow (1979), who provided the basic definition of a propositional proof system from the perspective of computational complexity.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Contemporary proof complexity research draws ideas and methods from many areas in computational complexity, algorithms and mathematics.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Since many important algorithms and algorithmic techniques can be cast as proof search algorithms for certain proof systems, proving lower bounds on proof sizes in these systems implies run-time lower bounds on the corresponding algorithms.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] This connects proof complexity to more applied areas such as SAT solving.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Mathematical logic can also serve as a framework to study propositional proof sizes.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] By default, proof theory discussed proof systems for classical propositional logic, using the **language** of propositional logic with the connectives $\land ,\lor ,\neg ,\to$ , and countably many propositional variables $\{p_{i}:i\in 2^{*}\}$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Here, $2^{*}$ is the set of finite binary strings.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A **proof system** is denoted with capital letters: $P,Q,R,\dots$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A **proof** is denoted with lowercase letters $x,y,z,\dots$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A **formula** is denoted with lower Greek letters: $\phi ,\psi ,\sigma ,\dots$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The **length** of a formula $\phi$ is $|\phi |$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Similarly, the length of a proof x is $|x|$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] TAUT is a formal language consisting of the tautological formulas of propositional logic.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Big-O and big-Omega notation are used in the same way as in computational complexity theory.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A proof system is an algorithm P that takes two inputs: a formula $\phi$ , and a purported proof x .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Examples of propositional proof systems include sequent calculus, resolution, cutting planes and Frege systems.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Strong mathematical theories such as ZFC induce propositional proof systems as well: a proof of a tautology $\tau$ in a propositional interpretation of ZFC is a ZFC-proof of a formalized statement ' $\tau$ is a tautology'.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A proof system can be thought of as a nondeterministic polynomial-time algorithm for proving non-satisfiability.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] That is, given a formula $\phi$ , $\phi$ is unsatisfiable if and only if there exists some x , such that $P(\neg \phi ,x)$ accepts.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] This shows its close relationship with the co-NP class.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Ordinary proof theory does not care about what formulas a certain proof system *can and cannot* prove.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Proof complexity is not satisfied with what *can* be done, but *how efficiently* it can be done, i.e. the computational complexity of the proof system.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In order to measure efficiency, what efficiency is for a proof system must be defined.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In ordinary complexity theory, efficiency can be measured by how many steps are required (time complexity), how much working space is required (space complexity), size of a Boolean circuit needed to implement a boolean function (circuit complexity), etc.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In proof complexity theory, there are also more than one way to measure of efficiency.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The **size complexity** of a proof system denotes the minimal size of proofs possible in the system for a given tautology.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In detail, a proof system has (upper bound) size complexity $O(F(n))$ iff given any tautology $\phi$ of length n , there is a proof of $\phi$ in this proof system that uses $\lesssim F(n)$ steps.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] It has (lower bound) size complexity $\Omega (F(n))$ iff given any length n , there exists a tautology $\phi$ of length n , such that any proof of $\phi$ in the proof system needs $\gtrsim F(n)$ steps.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The **space complexity** of a proof system denotes the memory usage during a proof.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A common way to measure "memory usage" is **clause complexity**: the maximum number of clauses that can appear simultaneously during a resolution proof.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The **search complexity** of a proof system denotes the computational complexity of a prover, that is, an algorithm for finding a proof of a tautology within a proof system.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A proof system with a polynomial-time prover is **automatable**.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A proof system P is polynomially bounded (**p-bounded**) iff for any $\phi$ , if there exists some x such that $P(\phi ,x)$ is true, then there exists some x such that $P(\phi ,x)$ is true, and $|x|={\mathsf {poly}}(|\phi |)$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In other words, anything that the system can prove at all, has a polynomially-short proof.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Most nontrivial proof systems are believed to be not p-bounded.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] To acquire intuition about why this is the case, one consider the following examples.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Given a graph $G=(V,E)$ , if there exists a 3-coloring, then this can be proven by simply giving the coloring.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Thus, the proof of 3-colorability has length $|V|$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In contrast, if there does *not* exist a 3-coloring, then there is no obvious way to prove it succinctly.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The naive way to prove it is to explicitly enumerate all $3^{|V|}$ possible 3-colorings, and showing that in each case, there are two vertices of the same color sharing an edge.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, such a proof is exponentially large compared to the input size.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The Hajós construction is a sound and complete proof system for graph non-3-colorability: A graph is non-3-colorable if and only if it has a Hajós 4-construction.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, such a construction may require superpolynomially steps.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Given a system of polynomials $f_{1}(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}),\dots ,f_{m}(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ in a finite field $\mathbb {F}$ , if there exists a root, then this can be proven by simply giving the values for the variables $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, if there is no root, then there is no obvious way to prove it succinctly.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The naive way to prove it is to explicitly enumerate all $|\mathbb {F} |^{n}$ possible values.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] By Hilbert's Nullstellensatz, there is a sound and complete proof system for non-solvability: There exists some polynomials $g_{1},\dots ,g_{m}$ such that $\sum _{i=1}^{m}g_{i}f_{i}=1$ , if and only if the polynomial system is non-solvable.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, the polynomials $g_{1},\dots ,g_{m}$ may contain superpolynomially many terms.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Given a formula $\phi$ in classical propositional logic with propositional variables $p_{1},\dots ,p_{n}$ , if it is not a tautology, then this can be proven by simply giving the truth-values for the propositional variables $p_{1},\dots ,p_{n}$ , such that $\phi$ evaluates to False.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, if it is a tautology, then there is no obvious way to prove it succinctly.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The naive way to prove it is to explicitly enumerate the truth table, which has $2^{n}$ rows.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] There are many sound and complete proof systems for proving tautologies of classical propositional logic, but there is no guarantee that any system can prove all tautologies with proof size ${\mathsf {poly}}(|\phi |)$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Does there exist a p-bounded proof system for classical propositional tautologies?
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Because $\phi$ is not a tautology if and only if $\neg \phi$ is satisfiable, ${\mathsf {TAUT}}$ is co-NP-complete.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Thus, if there exists a proof system for ${\mathsf {TAUT}}$ that is p-bounded, then NP = co-NP.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Conversely, if NP = co-NP, then ${\mathsf {TAUT}}$ , being co-NP, would also be NP, and thus there is a p-bounded proof system for proving tautologies.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] This was first proven by Cook and Reckhow (1979).
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Proof complexity compares the strength of proof systems using the notion of *efficient simulation*.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Efficiency is the operative concept here, since proof complexity theory studies not merely whether something can be proven, but in the efficiency of the proof.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Since a polynomial-time algorithm can only produce a polynomial-size output, p-simulation implies simulation.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The converse may not hold, i.e. two proof systems $P,Q$ may exist such that P simulates Q , but P does not p-simulate Q .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Both simulation and p-simulation relations are reflexive and transitive, thus they are preorders, and induces equivalence relations.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] If $P,Q$ (p-)simulate each other, then they are **(p-)equivalent**.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A proof system is **(p-)optimal** if it (p-)simulates all other proof systems.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Any nonempty set in NP has an optimal proof system.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] No set outside of NP is known to have an optimal proof system.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Any coNE-hard sets and even all coNQP-hard sets is known to have no optimal proof systems.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Sequent calculus is p-equivalent to (every) Frege system.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Every propositional proof system *P* can be simulated by Extended Frege extended with axioms postulating soundness of *P*.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Does there exist a p-optimal or optimal propositional proof system?
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] An optimal or p-optimal propositional proof system would be ideal in a sense, since it would produce the shortest (up to a polynomial factor) possible proofs for all tautologies.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] It has been proven that many weak proof systems cannot simulate certain stronger systems (see below).
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, the question remains open if the notion of simulation is relaxed.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] For example, it is open whether Resolution *effectively polynomially simulates* Extended Frege.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The second requirement incorporates the proviso of "the shortest *P*-proof of $\tau$ ", so that even if P is not polynomially bounded, it can still be automatable.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] That is, there may be tautologies such that the proof system *P* is forced to prove with proofs that are growing super-polynomially.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Nevertheless, the prover does the best it could out of a bad situation.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Many proof systems of interest are believed to be non-automatable.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, currently only conditional negative results are known.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] It is not known if the weak automatability of Resolution would break any standard complexity-theoretic hardness assumptions.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Propositional proof systems can be interpreted as nonuniform equivalents of theories of higher order.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The equivalence is most often studied in the context of theories of bounded arithmetic.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] For example, the Extended Frege system corresponds to Cook's theory $\mathrm {PV} _{1}$ formalizing polynomial-time reasoning and the Frege system corresponds to the theory $\mathrm {VNC} ^{1}$ formalizing ${\mathsf {NC}}^{1}$ reasoning.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The correspondence was introduced by Stephen Cook (1975), who showed that coNP theorems, formally $\Pi _{1}^{b}$ formulas, of the theory $\mathrm {PV} _{1}$ translate to sequences of tautologies with polynomial-size proofs in Extended Frege.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Moreover, Extended Frege is the weakest such system: if another proof system *P* has this property, then *P* simulates Extended Frege.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] An alternative translation between second-order statements and propositional formulas given by Jeff Paris and Alex Wilkie (1985) has been more practical for capturing subsystems of Extended Frege such as Frege or constant-depth Frege.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] While the above-mentioned correspondence says that proofs in a theory translate to sequences of short proofs in the corresponding proof system, a form of the opposite implication holds as well.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] It is possible to derive lower bounds on size of proofs in a proof system *P* by constructing suitable models of a theory *T* corresponding to the system *P*.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] This allows to prove complexity lower bounds via model-theoretic constructions, an approach known as Ajtai's method.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Propositional proof systems can be interpreted as nondeterministic algorithms for recognizing tautologies.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Proving a superpolynomial lower bound on a proof system *P* thus rules out the existence of a polynomial-time algorithm for SAT based on *P*.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] For example, runs of the DPLL algorithm on unsatisfiable instances correspond to tree-like Resolution refutations.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Therefore, exponential lower bounds for tree-like Resolution (see below) rule out the existence of efficient DPLL algorithms for SAT.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Similarly, exponential Resolution lower bounds imply that SAT solvers based on Resolution, such as CDCL algorithms cannot solve SAT efficiently (in worst-case).
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Proving lower bounds on lengths of propositional proofs is generally very difficult.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Nevertheless, several methods for proving lower bounds for weak proof systems have been discovered.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] It is a long-standing open problem to derive a nontrivial lower bound for the Frege system.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Consider a tautology of the form $A(x,y)\rightarrow B(y,z)$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The tautology is true for every choice of y , and after fixing y the evaluation of A and B are independent because they are defined on disjoint sets of variables.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] This means that it is possible to define an *interpolant* circuit $C(y)$ , such that both $A(x,y)\rightarrow C(y)$ and $C(y)\rightarrow B(y,z)$ hold.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The interpolant circuit decides either if $A(x,y)$ is false or if $B(y,z)$ is true, by only considering y .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The nature of the interpolant circuit can be arbitrary.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Nevertheless, it is possible to use a proof of the initial tautology $A(x,y)\rightarrow B(y,z)$ as a hint on how to construct C .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] A proof systems *P* is said to have *feasible interpolation* if the interpolant $C(y)$ is efficiently computable from any proof of the tautology $A(x,y)\rightarrow B(y,z)$ in *P*.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The efficiency is measured with respect to the length of the proof: it is easier to compute interpolants for longer proofs, so this property seems to be anti-monotone in the strength of the proof system.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] The following three statements cannot be simultaneously true: (a) $A(x,y)\rightarrow B(y,z)$ has a short proof in a some proof system; (b) such proof system has feasible interpolation; (c) the interpolant circuit solves a computationally hard problem.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] It is clear that (a) and (b) imply that there is a small interpolant circuit, which is in contradiction with (c).
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Such relation allows the conversion of proof length upper bounds into lower bounds on computations, and dually to turn efficient interpolation algorithms into lower bounds on proof length.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Some proof systems such as Resolution and Cutting Planes admit feasible interpolation or its variants.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Feasible interpolation can be seen as a weak form of automatability.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] In fact, for many proof systems, such as Extended Frege, feasible interpolation is equivalent to weak automatability.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Specifically, many proof systems *P* are able to prove their own soundness, which is a tautology $\mathrm {Ref} _{P}(\pi ,\phi ,x)$ stating that `if $\pi$ is a *P*-proof of a formula $\phi (x)$ then $\phi (x)$ holds'.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Here, $\pi ,\phi ,x$ are encoded by free variables.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Moreover, it is possible to generate *P*-proofs of $\mathrm {Ref} _{P}(\pi ,\phi ,x)$ in polynomial-time given the length of $\pi$ and $\phi$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Therefore, an efficient interpolant resulting from short *P*-proofs of soundness of *P* would decide whether a given formula $\phi$ admits a short *P*-proof $\pi$ .
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Such an interpolant can be used to define a proof system *R* witnessing that *P* is weakly automatable.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] On the other hand, weak automatability of a proof system *P* implies that *P* admits feasible interpolation.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] However, if a proof system *P* does not prove efficiently its own soundness, then it might not be weakly automatable even if it admits feasible interpolation.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Many non-automatability results provide evidence against feasible interpolation in the respective systems.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Many of these questions can be asked about propositional non-classical logics too, such as intuitionistic, modal, and non-monotonic logics.
[src:proof-complexity/proof-complexity] Hrubeš (2007–2009) proved exponential lower bounds on size of proofs in the Extended Frege system in some modal logics and in intuitionistic logic using a version of monotone feasible interpolation.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] In propositional calculus and proof complexity a **propositional proof system** (**pps**), also called a **Cook–Reckhow propositional proof system**, is a system for proving classical propositional tautologies.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] Formally a pps is a polynomial-time function *P* whose range is the set of all propositional tautologies (denoted TAUT).
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] If *A* is a formula, then any *x* such that *P*(*x*) = *A* is called a *P*-proof of *A*.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] In general, a proof system for a language *L* is a polynomial-time function whose range is *L*.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] Thus, a propositional proof system is a proof system for TAUT.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] Sometimes the following alternative definition is considered: a pps is given as a proof-verification algorithm *P*(*A*,*x*) with two inputs.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] If *P* accepts the pair (*A*,*x*) we say that *x* is a *P*-proof of *A*.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] *P* is required to run in polynomial time, and moreover, it must hold that *A* has a *P*-proof if and only if it is a tautology.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] If *P*1 is a pps according to the first definition, then *P*2 defined by *P*2(*A*,*x*) if and only if *P*1(*x*) = *A* is a pps according to the second definition.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] (*P*1 takes pairs as input) is a pps according to the first definition, where $\top$ is a fixed tautology.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] One can view the second definition as a non-deterministic algorithm for solving membership in TAUT.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] This means that proving a superpolynomial proof size lower-bound for pps would rule out existence of a certain class of polynomial-time algorithms based on that pps.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] As an example, exponential proof size lower-bounds in resolution for the pigeon hole principle imply that any algorithm based on resolution cannot decide TAUT or SAT efficiently and will fail on pigeon hole principle tautologies.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] This is significant because the class of algorithms based on resolution includes most of current propositional proof search algorithms and modern industrial SAT solvers.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] Historically, Frege's propositional calculus was the first propositional proof system.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] The general definition of a propositional proof system is due to Stephen Cook and Robert A.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] Propositional proof system can be compared using the notion of p-simulation.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] A propositional proof system *P* *p-simulates* *Q* (written as *P* ≤*p**Q*) when there is a polynomial-time function *F* such that *P*(*F*(*x*)) = *Q*(*x*) for every *x*.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] That is, given a *Q*-proof *x*, we can find in polynomial time a *P*-proof of the same tautology.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] There is also a weaker notion of simulation: a pps *P* *simulates* or *weakly p-simulates* a pps *Q* if there is a polynomial *p* such that for every *Q*-proof *x* of a tautology *A*, there is a *P*-proof *y* of *A* such that the length of *y*, |*y*| is at most *p*(|*x*|).
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] A propositional proof system is called *p-optimal* if it *p*-simulates all other propositional proof systems, and it is *optimal* if it simulates all other pps.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] A propositional proof system *P* is *polynomially bounded* (also called super) if every tautology has a short (i.e., polynomial-size) *P*-proof.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] If *P* is polynomially bounded and *Q* simulates *P*, then *Q* is also polynomially bounded.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] The set of propositional tautologies, TAUT, is a coNP-complete set.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] A propositional proof system is a certificate-verifier for membership in TAUT.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] Existence of a polynomially bounded propositional proof system means that there is a verifier with polynomial-size certificates, i.e., TAUT is in NP.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] In fact these two statements are equivalent, i.e., there is a polynomially bounded propositional proof system if and only if the complexity classes NP and coNP are equal.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] "Extended Frege" systems (allowing the introduction of new variables by definition) correspond in this way to polynomially-bounded systems, for example.
[src:proof-complexity/propositional-proof-system] Where the bounded arithmetic in turn corresponds to a circuit-based complexity class, there are often similarities between the theory of proof systems and the theory of the circuit families, such as matching lower bound results and separations.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] In mathematical logic and automated theorem proving, **resolution** is a rule of inference leading to a refutation-complete theorem-proving technique for sentences in propositional logic and first-order logic.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] For propositional logic, systematically applying the resolution rule acts as a decision procedure for formula unsatisfiability, solving the (complement of the) Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] For first-order logic, resolution can be used as the basis for a semi-algorithm for the unsatisfiability problem of first-order logic, providing a more practical method than one following from Gödel's completeness theorem.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The resolution rule can be traced back to Davis and Putnam (1960); however, their algorithm required trying all ground instances of the given formula.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] This source of combinatorial explosion was eliminated in 1965 by John Alan Robinson's syntactical unification algorithm, which allowed one to instantiate the formula during the proof "on demand" just as far as needed to keep refutation completeness.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The clause produced by a resolution rule is sometimes called a **resolvent**.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The **resolution rule** in propositional logic is a single valid inference rule that produces a new clause implied by two clauses containing complementary literals.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] A literal is a propositional variable or the negation of a propositional variable.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Two literals are said to be complements if one is the negation of the other (in the following, $\lnot c$ is taken to be the complement to c ).
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The resulting clause contains all the literals that do not have complements.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The clause produced by the resolution rule is called the *resolvent* of the two input clauses.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] It is the principle of *consensus* applied to clauses rather than terms.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] When the two clauses contain more than one pair of complementary literals, the resolution rule can be applied (independently) for each such pair; however, the result is always a tautology.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Modus ponens can be seen as a special case of resolution (of a one-literal clause and a two-literal clause).
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] When coupled with a complete search algorithm, the resolution rule yields a sound and complete algorithm for deciding the *satisfiability* of a propositional formula, and, by extension, the validity of a sentence under a set of axioms.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] This resolution technique uses proof by contradiction and is based on the fact that any sentence in propositional logic can be transformed into an equivalent sentence in conjunctive normal form.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] One instance of this algorithm is the original Davis–Putnam algorithm that was later refined into the DPLL algorithm that removed the need for explicit representation of the resolvents.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] This description of the resolution technique uses a set *S* as the underlying data-structure to represent resolution derivations.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Lists, Trees and Directed Acyclic Graphs are other possible and common alternatives.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Tree representations are more faithful to the fact that the resolution rule is binary.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Together with a sequent notation for clauses, a tree representation also makes it clear to see how the resolution rule is related to a special case of the cut-rule, restricted to atomic cut-formulas.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] However, tree representations are not as compact as set or list representations, because they explicitly show redundant subderivations of clauses that are used more than once in the derivation of the empty clause.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Graph representations can be as compact in the number of clauses as list representations and they also store structural information regarding which clauses were resolved to derive each resolvent.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] In order for the premise $a\vee b$ to be true, b must be true.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] In order for the premise $\neg a\vee c$ to be true, c must be true.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Therefore, regardless of falsehood or veracity of a , if both premises hold, then the conclusion $b\vee c$ is true.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] where $\phi$ is a most general unifier of $L_{1}$ and ${\overline {L_{2}}}$ , and $\Gamma _{1}$ and $\Gamma _{2}$ have no common variables.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The clauses $P(x),Q(x)$ and $\neg P(b)$ can apply this rule with $[b/x]$ as unifier.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Here x is a variable and b is a constant.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] In first-order logic, resolution condenses the traditional syllogisms of logical inference down to a single rule.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] To recast the reasoning using the resolution technique, first the clauses must be converted to conjunctive normal form (CNF).
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] In this form, all quantification becomes implicit: universal quantifiers on variables (*X*, *Y*, ...) are simply omitted as understood, while existentially-quantified variables are replaced by Skolem functions.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] So the question is, how does the resolution technique derive the last clause from the first two?
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] *X* is an unbound variable, while *a* is a bound value (term).
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Now, unifying *Q*(*X*) in the first clause with ¬*Q*(*Y*) in the second clause means that *X* and *Y* become the same variable anyway.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The resolution rule, as defined by Robinson, also incorporated factoring, which unifies two literals in the same clause, before or during the application of resolution as defined above.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The resulting inference rule is refutation-complete, in that a set of clauses is unsatisfiable if and only if there exists a derivation of the empty clause using only resolution, enhanced by factoring.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Since each clause consists of two literals, so does each possible resolvent.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Therefore, by resolution without factoring, the empty clause can never be obtained.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Generalizations of the above resolution rule have been devised that do not require the originating formulas to be in clausal normal form.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] These techniques are useful mainly in interactive theorem proving where it is important to preserve human readability of intermediate result formulas.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Besides, they avoid combinatorial explosion during transformation to clause-form, and sometimes save resolution steps.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Here $F[p]$ and $G[p]$ denote formulas containing p as a subformula. $F[{\textit {true}}]$ is built by replacing every occurrence of p in $F[p]$ by ${\textit {true}}$ .
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Similarly, $G[{\textit {false}}]$ is built by replacing every occurrence of p in $G[p]$ by ${\textit {false}}$ .
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The resolvent $F[{\textit {true}}]\lor G[{\textit {false}}]$ is intended to be simplified using rules like $q\land {\textit {true}}\implies q$ , etc.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] In order to prevent generating useless trivial resolvents, the rule is applied only when p has at least one "negative" and "positive" occurrence in F and G , respectively.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Murray has shown that this rule is complete if augmented by appropriate logical transformation rules.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] where the exponents of p indicate the polarity of its occurrences.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] While $G[{\textit {true}}]$ and $G[{\textit {false}}]$ are built as before, the formula $F[G[{\textit {true}}],\lnot G[{\textit {false}}]]$ is obtained by replacing each positive occurrence of p in F with $G[{\textit {true}}]$ and each negative occurrence with $G[{\textit {false}}]$ .
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Similar to Murray's approach, appropriate simplifying transformations are to be applied to the resolvent.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Traugott proved his rule to be complete, provided $\land ,\lor ,\rightarrow ,\lnot$ are the only connectives used in formulas.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Traugott's resolvent is stronger than Murray's.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Moreover, it does not introduce new binary junctors, thus avoiding a tendency towards clausal form in repeated resolution.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] However, formulas may grow longer when a small p is replaced multiple times with a larger $G[{\textit {true}}]$ and/or $G[{\textit {false}}]$ .
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] For first-order predicate logic, Murray's rule is generalized to allow distinct, but unifiable, subformulas $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ of F and G , respectively.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] If $\phi$ is the most general unifier of $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ , then the generalized resolvent is $F\phi [{\textit {true}}]\lor G\phi [{\textit {false}}]$ .
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] While the rule remains sound if a more special substitution $\phi$ is used, no such rule applications are needed to achieve completeness.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Traugott's rule is generalized to allow several pairwise distinct subformulas $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{m}$ of F and $p_{m+1},\ldots ,p_{n}$ of G , as long as $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{n}$ have a common most general unifier, say $\phi$ .
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The generalized resolvent is obtained after applying $\phi$ to the parent formulas, thus making the propositional version applicable.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Traugott's completeness proof relies on the assumption that this fully general rule is used; it is not clear whether his rule would remain complete if restricted to $p_{1}=\cdots =p_{m}$ and $p_{m+1}=\cdots =p_{n}$ .
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] Paramodulation is a related technique for reasoning on sets of clauses where the predicate symbol is equality.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] It generates all "equal" versions of clauses, except reflexive identities.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The paramodulation operation takes a positive *from* clause, which must contain an equality literal.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] It then searches an *into* clause with a subterm that unifies with one side of the equality.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The subterm is then replaced by the other side of the equality.
[src:proof-complexity/resolution-logic] The general aim of paramodulation is to reduce the system to atoms, reducing the size of the terms when substituting.
